    "Name": "taxonomy_of_failure_modes_in_vlm_autonomous_driving",
    "Title": "Taxonomy of Failure Modes in Vision-Language Models for Autonomous Driving",
    "Short Hypothesis": "There is a need to systematically categorize and analyze failure modes in vision-language models (VLMs) for autonomous driving to improve their robustness and reliability. This research aims to develop a comprehensive taxonomy that encompasses various failure modes and to study their impact on the performance of VLMs.",
    "Related Work": "While recent works have explored the potential of VLMs in autonomous driving, such as Elhafsi et al. (2023) on semantic anomaly detection, Zhou et al. (2025) on AutoVLA for enhanced reasoning, and Qian et al. (2025) on AgentThink for tool-augmented reasoning, there is a gap in understanding the failure modes of these models in real-world scenarios. Our work differs by focusing on cataloging and analyzing these failure modes rather than on the positive aspects of the models. Moreover, Tian et al. (2025) have introduced NuScenes-SpatialQA to evaluate spatial reasoning, and Wang et al. (2025) have proposed CAD for black-box adversarial attacks, both highlighting potential failure modes. Our taxonomy aims to be more comprehensive, covering various aspects, and providing insights into improving VLM robustness.",
    "Abstract": "Vision-Language Models (VLMs) have shown promise in enhancing autonomous driving capabilities, yet they often exhibit unexpected failures and robustness gaps when deployed in real-world scenarios. To address this issue, we propose a research direction that focuses on systematically categorizing and analyzing failure modes in VLMs for autonomous driving. Our proposed taxonomy of failure modes encompasses various categories, including catastrophic distribution shifts, weak spatial-temporal consistency, hallucinatory reasoning, poor cross-scene generalization, and unstable fine-tuning dynamics. We aim to study the impact of these failure modes on model performance and safety-critical scenarios. Our work highlights the importance of understanding and addressing these failure modes to improve the reliability and robustness of VLMs in autonomous driving applications.",
    "Experiments": [
      "Perform a comprehensive literature review to identify and document reported failure modes in VLMs for autonomous driving.",
      "Develop a taxonomy categorizing the identified failure modes based on their nature, impact, and potential causes.",
      "Analyze the occurrences and impacts of these failure modes using quantitative metrics and case studies on diverse datasets.",
      "Conduct experiments to validate the effectiveness of proposed mitigation strategies in improving model robustness against identified failure modes."
