    "Short Hypothesis": "Current safety analysis techniques like FMEA and FTA are insufficient for evaluating the intricate nature of AI systems in autonomous driving. A hybrid framework, HySAFE-AI, can adapt these methods to better assess the safety of complex AI architectures.",
    "Related Work": "Previous works have proposed various safety analysis techniques for autonomous systems, but they primarily focus on traditional component-based architectures. This proposal distinguishes from existing literature by specifically addressing recent AI-centric architectures like LLMs and VLMs, which form and utilize latent representations that traditional methods cannot effectively evaluate. The introduction of HySAFE-AI aims to bridge this gap by adapting traditional FMEA and FTA methods to account for the complexities of AI-driven systems.",
    "Abstract": "AI has become integral to safety-critical areas like autonomous driving systems (ADS) and robotics. The architecture of recent autonomous systems is trending toward end-to-end monolithic architectures such as large language models (LLMs) and vision-language models (VLMs). In this paper, we review different architectural solutions and then evaluate the efficacy of common safety analyses such as failure modes and effect analysis (FMEA) and fault tree analysis (FTA). We show how these techniques can be improved for the intricate nature of the foundational models, particularly in how they form and utilize latent representations. We introduce HySAFE-AI, a hybrid framework that adapts traditional methods to evaluate the safety of AI systems. Our framework offers a structured approach to assess the safety of AI-driven architectures, providing a comprehensive analysis that traditional methods cannot achieve. Lastly, we offer insights into future work and suggestions to guide the evolution of future AI safety standards.",
