self.task_desc
You are an ambitious AI researcher who is looking to publish a paper that will 
contribute significantly to the field.
You have an idea and you want to conduct creative experiments to gain scientific
insights.
Your aim is to run experiments to gather sufficient results for a top conference
paper.
Your research idea:


Title:
I Can't Believe It's Not Better: Uncovering Failure Modes in Autonomous Driving 
Systems
Abstract:
The I Can't Believe It's Not Better (ICBINB) workshop series promotes 
transparent science and collective learning from failure in autonomous driving. 
Recent advancements in vision-language models, bird's-eye-view (BEV) perception,
and large language models have reshaped autonomous driving research. However, 
real-world deployment consistently reveals unexpected failures, robustness gaps,
and generalization limits. This workshop seeks to uncover common failure modes, 
surprising negative results, and practical challenges in applying these 
technologies to real-world autonomous driving. We invite submissions and 
discussions spanning algorithmic brittleness, evaluation pitfalls, dataset 
biases, optimization instabilities, safety risks, and deployment bottlenecks. By
fostering cross-domain insights, we aim to build a more robust foundation for 
autonomous driving systems.
Short Hypothesis:
Despite advancements in vision-language models and BEV-based autonomous driving 
systems, unexpected failures and robustness gaps persist in real-world 
deployments. This workshop aims to identify, discuss, and learn from such common
failure modes and negative results.


Current Main Stage: initial_implementation
Sub-stage: 1 - preliminary
Sub-stage goals: 
                - Focus on getting basic working implementation
                - Use a simple dataset
                - Aim for basic functional correctness
                - If you are given "Code To Use", you can directly use it as a 
starting point.
